Use MSTest's **`[DynamicData]`** to make it data-driven. One method handles all cases, and adding a new test is just adding a row:

```csharp
using Microsoft.VisualStudio.TestTools.UnitTesting;

namespace Validation.Tests;

[TestClass]
public sealed class InputValidatorTests
{
    private static IEnumerable<object?[]> ValidationCases =>
    [
        [null,                  false, "Input cannot be empty",                 "Null"],
        ["",                    false, "Input cannot be empty",                 "Empty string"],
        ["   ",                 false, "Input cannot be empty",                 "Whitespace only"],
        ["ab",                  false, "Input must be at least 3 characters",   "Too short"],
        [new string('x', 256), false, "Input must not exceed 255 characters",  "Too long"],
        ["hello<script>",      false, "Input contains invalid characters",     "Special chars"],
        ["abc",                 true,  null,                                    "Min length"],
        [new string('a', 255), true,  null,                                    "Max length"],
        ["hello-world",        true,  null,                                    "Valid input"],
    ];

    [DataTestMethod]
    [DynamicData(nameof(ValidationCases))]
    public void Validate_ReturnsExpectedResult(
        string? input, bool expectedValid, string? expectedError, string _scenario)
    {
        var validator = new InputValidator();

        var result = validator.Validate(input);

        Assert.AreEqual(expectedValid, result.IsValid);
        Assert.AreEqual(expectedError, result.ErrorMessage);
    }
}
```

**Key benefits:**

- **Adding a case** = adding one line to the array
- **`[DynamicData]`** over `[DataRow]` because `DataRow` requires compile-time constants (can't do `new string('x', 256)`)
- The `_scenario` parameter gives each test a readable name in the test runner
- The `ValidationCases` property is a collection expression (`[...]`) — works in C# 12+; use `new[]` syntax for older versions
